        "timestamp": "2020-06-19 15:13:22.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> \n> This change removes the autowired annotation making this class throw null pointers when not under test.\n\nHi Max, as of Spring 4.3, classes with a single constructor can omit the @Autowired annotation.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "2223d41b01376b3a3236e6c0b20dd43829bf9868",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 97,
          "name": "Max Benjamin",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "max.benjamin@att.com",
          "username": "mfour"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-06-19 15:27:42.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> \n> > Patch Set 1:\n> > \n> > This change removes the autowired annotation making this class throw null pointers when not under test.\n> \n> Hi Max, as of Spring 4.3, classes with a single constructor can omit the @Autowired annotation.\n\nOkay no problem. It's just that all the other classes use @InjectMocks in the unit test for @Autowired fields and this one was a different style. I am not sure if we should have two styles of doing this. I will be putting up a changeset with @InjectMocks and we can discuss it further.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      }
